---
import LightLayout from '../../../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="Script · Google Maps" description="Structured script by blocks for Stripe Product Sense. Read aloud to internalise the structure.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 pb-6">
    <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Back to hub</a>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mt-6 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">🗺️</span>
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black !my-0" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Script · Google Maps</h1>
        <p class="!my-1 font-medium" style="color: var(--color-primary);">~7 min read aloud · 7 blocks + transplant</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="flex gap-2 flex-wrap text-xs">
      <span class="px-2 py-1 rounded" style="background: var(--color-mist); color: var(--color-stone);">Question: "Talk about a product you use"</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="prose-factory">

      <div class="card !p-5 my-6" style="background: rgba(236,72,153,0.10); border: 1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.25);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">📌 How to use this script</h3>
        <p class="!mb-0">Read it aloud three times. Don't memorise words, memorise <strong>the order of the blocks</strong>. The grey boxes on the right are your internal annotations (why each move works), <strong>don't say them out loud</strong>. The transplant at the end is where you'll win the interview the most.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[USER]</h2>
      <p>"OK. I'm going to talk about <strong>Google Maps</strong>, which I use every day. My primary user is not 'the person who needs to get from A to B', because that covers everyone. <strong>My primary user is the urban commuter</strong>, someone who moves around the same city 2 to 5 times a day, with repeated routes but changing conditions."</p>
      <p>"I'm choosing this user because it's the segment where Google Maps drives the most recurring usage and where a product change has measurable returns. Other segments, the city visitor, the delivery driver, I'll touch on as contrast, but my focus is the commuter."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Applies pattern 1 (user defined + justified) and pattern 4 (explicit focus). "I'll touch on as contrast" closes the move without sounding inflexible.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[SUB-SEGMENTS]</h2>
      <p>"Within the urban commuter I distinguish three sub-segments based on how they use Maps."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>The optimiser.</strong> Knows the routes but wants to know which one is best today. Opens Maps 30 seconds before leaving."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The explorer.</strong> Knows the city but tries new routes, maybe for traffic, maybe to discover. Keeps the app open during the trip."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The multimodal.</strong> Switches between car, bike, public transport depending on the day. Needs to compare options, not just see one."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"I'm going to focus on the optimiser, because it's the most frequent and where Maps' promise is clearest: 'tell me which route is best right now'. I'll come back to the others if you ask."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 2: sub-segmentation by behaviour, not demographics. Each sub-segment is defined by how they use the product, not by age or gender.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[ECOSYSTEM]</h2>
      <p>"Before talking about what I'd change, I want to situate Maps in its ecosystem. Maps plays on three boards."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>User attention</strong>, competing with Apple Maps, Waze, Citymapper, and in some regions with local apps."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Data quality</strong>, where it doesn't compete with apps but with OpenStreetMap, with the users themselves who report incidents, and with telemetry feeds from connected cars."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Indirect monetisation</strong>, where Maps is a traffic provider for Google Search and Google Ads, not directly monetised itself. Product decisions have to hold on that board too."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"Any proposal I make has to win on at least one of those three boards without losing on the others."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 3 (mapping the ecosystem). This stops your proposals from sounding like feature dump. It's the pattern that differentiates the most in a Stripe interview according to your reconnaissance.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[THE INVISIBLE FEATURE]</h2>
      <p>"Before I propose anything, I want to name something Maps does that goes unnoticed: <strong>search is not just search</strong>. When you type 'pharmacy', Maps doesn't return pharmacies sorted by distance, it returns pharmacies <strong>filtered by which ones are open right now</strong>. That product decision, invisible, is what turns Maps into a daily assistant instead of an interactive map."</p>
      <p>"I bring it up because my proposal builds on that logic: <strong>the right information is not the complete information, it's the actionable-now information</strong>."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 "The invisible feature" is your anchor frame for Google Maps. It separates you from candidates who only describe what's obvious. Memorise that sentence.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[PROPOSAL]</h2>
      <p>"For the optimiser, I propose <strong>anticipated route-change prediction</strong>. Today Maps tells me the best route when I ask. My proposal: Maps proactively notifies me 5 minutes before I usually leave if my habitual route is going to be worse than normal, without me asking."</p>
      <p>"It connects directly to the sub-segment I chose: the optimiser doesn't want to open the app, they want the app to reach them when it matters. <strong>And it serves the invisible-feature promise: the right information when it's actionable</strong>, not when the user requests it."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 5: the proposal is tied to a sub-segment and a product promise. It doesn't float.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[EDGE CASES]</h2>
      <p>"Before I close, three edge cases I have to solve."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, false positives. If the alert fires when there was no real problem, I lose trust. Mitigation: conservative threshold, only alert when the delta exceeds, say, 8 minutes over the median of that trip."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, the user who has no habitual routes (tourist). The alert is meaningless. Solution: the feature only activates when a pattern is detected, not by default."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, privacy. To predict patterns I have to know where the user goes. Solution: explicit opt-in, and on-device processing when possible, not server-side."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[RISKS: TIGER + PAPER TIGER]</h2>
      <p>"I see one real Tiger and one Paper Tiger."</p>
      <p>"<strong>🐅 Tiger:</strong> notification fatigue. If Maps starts pushing alerts, even useful ones, the user can disable notifications at the system level and we lose the channel. Mitigation: at most one alert per trip, and learn from engagement; if the user ignores three in a row, the feature deactivates itself."</p>
      <p>"<strong>📰 Paper Tiger:</strong> 'Waze already does this'. It looks plausible but doesn't hold. Waze alerts <em>during</em> the trip, not before. The difference is timing: <strong>pre-trip vs in-trip</strong>. They're two different products, they don't compete on the same axis."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 7 executed cleanly. The Paper Tiger dismantles the most obvious competitive assumption with a precise temporal distinction. This lifts Critical Thinking.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[METRICS]</h2>
      <p>"Metrics on four layers."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Target:</strong> average minutes saved per user per week on their habitual commute. North Star because it measures delivered value, not engagement with the feature."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Leading:</strong> alert acceptance rate in the first 7 days. Target 60%."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Lagging:</strong> retention of the optimiser at 6 months with the feature on vs off. Target +5pp."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Guard rail:</strong> share of users who disable Maps notifications at the system level. Cannot rise more than 1% absolute."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[TRANSPLANT]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine the interviewer says: 'OK, now do it for rural areas in developing countries'."</p>
      <p>"<strong>OK, let me pause here, because the context changes the problem.</strong> For rural areas in developing countries, at least three assumptions I was making break down."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, I was assuming continuous connectivity. In rural areas without stable 4G, anticipated prediction can't depend on a server. I have to rethink it as on-device modelling plus pre-cached data."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, I was assuming recurring habitual routes. In a rural context there's often no daily commute but variable trips (market, hospital, school), with much less data density. The habitual-pattern feature doesn't apply."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, I was assuming a certain digital infrastructure (modern smartphone, enough data, reliable battery). In rural contexts all of that varies. The feature has to work on low-end devices and consume little battery."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"With those assumptions broken, my proposal transforms. Instead of 'anticipated route-change prediction', I'd propose <strong>a geofenced road-condition reporting system, validated by local users and pre-cached for offline use</strong>. It moves from a predictive feature to a collaborative one. And it serves the rural user better, who has fewer options when a route is closed."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 9 in its cleanest form. Explicit pause, naming 3 broken assumptions, then redesign. If you do this well, you win the interview right here.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[IF THEY PUSH BACK]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine the interviewer pushes: 'but the commuter already has Waze warning them, aren't you reinventing the wheel?'"</p>
      <p>"Good question. Let me distinguish two things I was conflating. <strong>Alerting during the trip</strong> is what Waze does, and it does it well. <strong>Alerting before the trip</strong>, at the moment when the user can still change their departure time or their mode of transport, is a different product. The difference isn't a feature, it's a moment: the first product is for reacting, the second product is for deciding. My proposal lives in the second plane, it doesn't compete with the first."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 10: reformulating with a finer distinction (reacting vs deciding). You don't defend the original sentence, you open a new distinction.</p>
      </div>

      <hr class="my-10" />

      <div class="card !p-6 my-8" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">🎯 The three anchor sentences to memorise</h3>
        <ol class="!mb-0">
          <li><strong>"The right information is not the complete information, it's the actionable-now information"</strong> (the invisible feature).</li>
          <li><strong>"Pre-trip vs in-trip are two different products"</strong> (the Paper Tiger against Waze).</li>
          <li><strong>"Reacting vs deciding"</strong> (the finer distinction under pressure).</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-3 mt-10">
        <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Hub</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/steam" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Next: Steam →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</LightLayout>
